04256nam a22006615i 9780271096025DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710960257 a10.1515/97802710960252doi  a(DE-B1597)677959  a(OCoLC)1399385830  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0151002bisacsh04a709.2qOCoLC223/eng/202304051 aCasini, Giovanni, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLéonce Rosenberg’s Cubism :bThe Galerie L’Effort Moderne in Interwar Paris /cGiovanni Casini. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (254 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRefiguring Modernism00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Cubism and Tradition -- t2. Masters of Cubism -- t3. Léonce Rosenberg, Éditeur d’Art -- t4. The Nationality of Cubism: Cosmopolitanism and Rosenberg’s International Promotion of the Avant-Garde -- t5. 75 Rue de Longchamp -- tEpilogue: After L’Effort Moderne -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of modernism has generally been written as a story of artists and their creations alongside the collectors, gallerists, and curators who supported them. This is especially true of Cubism, where the received narrative centers on a tightly circumscribed group of artists and agents connected to the dealer Daniel-Henry Kahnweiler. Léonce Rosenberg’s Cubism shakes up the canon, revealing its artificial nature and pointing to a different, more inclusive understanding of the development of Cubism.Kahnweiler’s Cubism was narrowly focused. In contrast, Giovanni Casini shows us, the influential art dealer Léonce Rosenberg bought virtually any piece that could be labeled “Cubist” and proposed a radically different understanding of the movement. At Rosenberg’s Galerie L’Effort Moderne in Paris, artists such as Joseph Csáky, Auguste Herbin, Jean Metzinger, Diego Rivera, Gino Severini, and Georges Valmier were accorded the same treatment as Pablo Picasso or Georges Braque. In this book, Casini considers Rosenberg’s contribution to the history of Cubism, reflecting on the ways in which artistic movements are manufactured—and interpretive paradigms adopted.Deftly weaving biography with a scholarly analysis built on extensive archival research, Léonce Rosenberg’s Cubism is a fresh look at the history of interwar modernism and the definitive study of a figure who has been unjustly sidelined in the history of art. It will be compulsory reading for scholars of Cubism and Modernism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh  aAbstraction.  aAmbroise Vollard.  aArt Market.  aCubism.  aGalerie L’Effort Moderne.  aInterwar Period.  aJewish Dealers.  aKahnweiler.  aLéonce Rosenberg.  aModernism.  aNetworks.  aParis.  aPaul Guillaume.  aPaul Rosenberg.  aReturn to order.  apost-war classicism.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271096025?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271096025423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271096025/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles